sec.p:
Mitchell (2009) suggests four categories of evaluation:


diligence (enumeration of tasks performed);

effectiveness (the achievement of tangible impacts);

responsiveness (the satisfaction of wants);

sociability (the contribution to city life).
He concludes that: ‘The ultimate value of BIDs is their symbolism as tipping points and optimistic shapers of American cities’ (p. 109), which suggests that less tangible benefits may be as important as the more tangible outcomes. These may be of wider benefit both in terms of impact and in terms of establishing ways of achieving change through public/private partnership, but are difficult to isolate and measure.
